CHICKENPOX - VENEZUELA: (CAPITAL DISTRICT), NOSOCOMIAL, VACCINE SHORTAGE
************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 23 Jun 2015
Source: Venezuelaaldia.com [in Spanish, trans. K. Soderholm, edited]
http://www.venezuelaaldia.com/2015/06/para-colmo-no-hay-vacunas-brote-de-lechina-en-el-j-m-de-los-rios-obliga-a-restringir-admision-de-emergencias/


The detection of an outbreak of chicken pox forced the Medical Director of the Children's Hospital Jose Manuel de los Rios to restrict the admission of patients to the health center. A statement released yesterday [22 Jun 2015] by the hospital authorities informed medical personnel that at least 15 children were exposed to an extremely contagious viral infection.

"They recommend [restricting admissions to] the institution only for serious emergency cases, who will be located in areas selected for the care of unexposed and immune patients," said the statement signed by the medical director Juan Felix Garcia.

A source, who asked that we not reveal his identity, said that even emergencies were severely restricted. In that area, there are 2 patients diagnosed with chickenpox: a girl with a blood cancer who is on artificial ventilation, and other children with HIV and chronic malnutrition who are a source of infection for other children.

"The Infectious Diseases and Medical Services are trying to follow up on cases, but the whole hospital is exposed. For the past 6-8 months, there have been isolated cases in the health center; even some medical students have been infected, but [the current outbreak] is the most serious," he said.

Huniades Urbina, president of the Venezuelan Society of Childcare and Pediatrics, warned that there has been no chickenpox vaccine in the country since May 2014. The flaw, he explained, is global: "There are problems with the European and Asian strains that are used to make the vaccine. However, it must be noted that the Ministry of Health does not include the vaccine in their immunization schedule, so it would be available only at private schools, but there is no official information from the ministry about the deficit," he said.

Urbina said 2 doses of vaccine are needed to immunize patients against the disease. "Patients are at risk," he said.

